Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Phase-Flip Errors", "TechNoteSection",
 CellTags->"Section12",
 CellID->2033391278,ExpressionUUID->"d28f9e2e-7b1a-44cc-993d-4b486bc95439"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "As was already mentioned, a quantum state is a superposition of the logical \
basis state, and any modulation of the superposition coefficients without \
altering the logical basis states results in an error. In particular, a mere \
change in the relative phase in the coefficients leads to a deviation from \
the original state even though it does not change the occupation \
probabilities in the logical basis states. Let us consider an extreme case \
where the relative phase of a single qubit is shifted by \[Pi]\[LongDash]the \
relative sign of the superposition coefficients is flipped from ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"+", "1"}], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "485c5077-e112-41cc-a842-af2f65c46ff0"],
 " to ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"\[Minus]", "1"}], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "65bbc3ff-026e-4a81-aa94-2c7f4889b1c1"],
 ", and vice versa\[LongDash]with probability ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox["p", TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "461cee54-a376-4cf3-98fb-c8f6c39e7230"],
 ". It is called the phase-flip error, and the corresponding error operator \
is ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox["Z", TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "e7d17382-a338-4b2c-9a9d-a72f128c9df0"],
 ". Such an error is particularly interesting because it has no classical \
counterpart since classically, the phase does not play any role."
}], "TechNoteText",
 CellID->152450988,ExpressionUUID->"e6ebc95a-5f8e-4bfb-862d-6d62cce35b76"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "\tNevertheless, the phase-flip error is essentially no different from the \
bit-flip error. This becomes immediately clear when one observes that the \
phase-flip error switches the states ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    TemplateBox[{"\[PlusMinus]"},
     "Ket"], ":=", 
    RowBox[{
     RowBox[{"(", 
      RowBox[{
       TemplateBox[{"0"},
        "Ket"], "\[PlusMinus]", 
       TemplateBox[{"1"},
        "Ket"]}], ")"}], "/", 
     SqrtBox["2"]}]}], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "625325b1-9e6c-42f8-894f-75bb068f6948"],
 " to each other. Therefore, a change of basis from ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"{", 
    RowBox[{
     TemplateBox[{"0"},
      "Ket"], ",", 
     TemplateBox[{"1"},
      "Ket"]}], "}"}], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "69b157f2-778d-49a9-8404-c5e9a3b9648f"],
 " to ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"{", 
    RowBox[{
     TemplateBox[{"+"},
      "Ket"], ",", 
     TemplateBox[{"-"},
      "Ket"]}], "}"}], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "cb4d900e-00b4-4816-b5de-89ae65bdeb76"],
 " just converts the phase-flip error to the bit-flip error, which has \
already been addressed above. Apart from the proper choice of basis, the full \
error-correction procedure (including encoding, error-detection, and \
recovery) is the same as protecting against bit-flip errors. It seems ironic \
that the phase-flip error, which appears to be genuinely a quantum problem, \
can be countered by a basis change, another feature of quantum mechanics with \
no classical equivalent. This fact suggests that all types of errors can be \
handled on an equal footing, and it further inspires ideas for how to protect \
against general quantum noise."
}], "TechNoteText",
 CellID->295764445,ExpressionUUID->"e808f46f-43f7-4450-a5e0-958609ebe3e9"],

Cell["\<\
\tAlthough it is already clear from the above observations, for the sake of \
later use, we construct the procedure to protect against phase-flip errors. \
The encoding chooses\
\>", "TechNoteText",
 CellID->1635867957,ExpressionUUID->"f4604387-e89b-497d-8032-21de6e56c9f1"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "\t",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    TemplateBox[{
      OverscriptBox["0", "_"]},
     "Ket"], ":=", 
    TemplateBox[{
      RowBox[{"++", "+"}]},
     "Ket"]}], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "49ec40e0-6853-44f4-a813-8e8b689adf0c"],
 " ,    ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    TemplateBox[{
      OverscriptBox["1", "_"]},
     "Ket"], ":=", 
    TemplateBox[{
      RowBox[{"--", "-"}]},
     "Ket"]}], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "c4745135-1807-428c-900b-143c15034e38"]
}], "TechNoteText",
 CellID->1947104405,ExpressionUUID->"7a5df82d-99c3-40de-9935-826fc8388e93"],

Cell["\<\
as the local basis states. The unitary transformation to implement the \
encoding can be described by the quantum circuits in Figure 2. \
\>", "TechNoteText",
 CellID->1627921849,ExpressionUUID->"2c6bbc1b-be2e-4ec8-be5e-8ab06be486a1"],

