Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Arbitrary Errors", "TechNoteSection",
 CellTags->"Section13",
 CellID->18451360,ExpressionUUID->"9a6ab68e-ec4e-4318-aa1c-2396c0f3ad22"],

Cell["\<\
So far, we have considered specific types of errors, the bit-flip and \
phase-flip errors. Obviously, realistic errors are far more general, not only \
in terms of the above two but also with any continuous change of the complex \
amplitudes in superposition of quantum states. It may sound rather surprising \
at first glance, but it turns out that roughly speaking, if a quantum \
error-correction code can correct the bit-flip and phase-flip errors, then it \
can correct any arbitrary errors. Before we introduce the precise statement \
and the corresponding construction of the quantum error-correction code in \
subsequently sections, we provide an example here: Shor\[CloseCurlyQuote]s \
9-qubit code. This code just builds upon the bit-flip and phase-flip \
correction codes discussed above, and yet it corrects completely arbitrary \
single-qubit errors.\
\>", "TechNoteText",
 CellID->874362352,ExpressionUUID->"b8c72be0-ea06-4fd4-a855-b9d96a3456a0"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "\tAccording to the discussion above, protecting against the bit-flip and \
phase- flip error each requires for three qubits to encode one bit of \
physical quantum state. Hence, the encoding in Shor\[CloseCurlyQuote]s code \
needs 9 qubits to protect against both types of errors and their possible \
combinations. More specifically, following the phase-flip correction code, we \
first encode the physical basis states |0\:27e9 and |1\:27e9 in the \
three-qubit logical basis states ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   TemplateBox[{
     RowBox[{"++", "+"}]},
    "Ket"], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "289238b7-0211-45ca-a422-fd4d88e22c5d"],
 " and ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   TemplateBox[{
     RowBox[{"--", "-"}]},
    "Ket"], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "7d79fd77-095c-49be-8011-13990f10f06a"],
 " , and we then encode each single-qubit state on three qubits using the \
bit-flip encoding scheme, that is, ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   TemplateBox[{"+"},
    "Ket"], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "9cc20f8f-77d0-4728-b551-0960b0cccac0"],
 " by ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"(", 
     RowBox[{
      TemplateBox[{"000"},
       "Ket"], "+", 
      TemplateBox[{"111"},
       "Ket"]}], ")"}], "/", 
    SqrtBox["2"]}], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "e4197837-2e16-4189-8d17-5c4b867fd34a"],
 " and ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   TemplateBox[{"+"},
    "Ket"], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "b7a78799-f64e-4b25-a406-1f2136cc3583"],
 " by ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"(", 
     RowBox[{
      TemplateBox[{"000"},
       "Ket"], "-", 
      TemplateBox[{"111"},
       "Ket"]}], ")"}], "/", 
    SqrtBox["2"]}], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "8bd78113-0c86-45b2-a35a-dcf1a322d3d0"],
 ". One can regard that the phase-flip correction code is encoded on three \
blocks, and the bit-flip correction code on each block is encoded on the \
three qubits. The code words of the overall encoding are given by"
}], "TechNoteText",
 CellID->177453643,ExpressionUUID->"1170c6c7-6b89-4956-afc7-e4faee30b286"],

